leppo's notables organized their families in a great diversity of ways, despite the fact that they were all members of the same social class with widely shared cultural values, acting under the same system of family law. She concludes that this had important implications for gender relations and demonstrates that it gave women more authority and greater autonomy than is usually acknowledged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFamilieszMiddle EastxHistoryy18th century. 0aFamilieszMiddle EastxHistoryy19th century. 0aFamilieszSyriazAleppoxHistory. 0aMarriage - Syria - Aleppo - History. 0aMarriagezMiddle EastxHistoryy18th century. 0aMarriagezMiddle EastxHistoryy19th century. 0aMarriagezSyriazAleppoxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75223840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292757134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292757134/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK